{{Short description|Ancient tomb in Nara Prefecture, Japan}}
[[File:Kitora 201611a.jpg|250px|thumb|right|The Kitora Tomb]]
[[File:Kitora Tomb2.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Rear view of building that houses the Kitora Tomb]]
The {{nihongo|'''Kitora Tomb'''|キトラ古墳|''Kitora Kofun''}} is an ancient {{ill|Tumulus|en|Tumulus|qid=Q34023|lt=Tumulus|1=Tumulus}} (''[[kofun]]'' in Japanese) located in the [[:en:Villages of Japan|village]] of {{ill|Asuka, Nara|en|Asuka, Nara|qid=Q752397|lt=Asuka|1=Asuka, Nara}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|en|Nara Prefecture|qid=Q131287|lt=Nara Prefecture|1=Nara Prefecture}}, {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}. The tomb is believed to have been constructed some time between the 7th and early 8th centuries, but was only discovered in 1983.

A small stone chamber, the Kitora Tomb is a little over 1 metre in height and width and about 2.4 metres long, just large enough to bury a single person. The four walls are aligned with the cardinal points of the compass, and respectively feature the [[:en:Black Tortoise|Black Divine Tortoise]] of the North, the {{ill|Azure Dragon|en|Azure Dragon|qid=Q515882|lt=Azure Dragon|1=Azure Dragon}} of the East, the {{ill|Vermilion Bird|en|Vermilion Bird|qid=Q1059392|lt=Red Phoenix|1=Vermilion Bird}} of the South, and the [[:en:White Tiger (China)|White Tiger]] of the West. On the ceiling of the chamber there is also an astronomical chart that has been the focus of much research and debate by scholars in the field of {{ill|Archaeoastronomy|en|Archaeoastronomy|qid=Q463923|lt=Archaeoastronomy|1=Archaeoastronomy}}. In addition, the 12 zodiac animals-headed figures with human body are painted on the wall, which may be one of the oldest remaining zodiac murals in East Asia.

Fragments of a {{ill|Lacquer|en|Lacquer|qid=Q11236878|lt=Lacquer|1=Lacquer}}ed wooden coffin, torn apart when the tomb was robbed, lay 5&nbsp;cm thick on the chamber floor, mixed with grave goods and human bone. A gilded {{ill|Bronze|en|Bronze|qid=Q34095|lt=Bronze|1=Bronze}} fitting and sword decorations were discovered, both executed with superbly inlaid patterns. Based upon analysis of the bone fragments and items found in the tomb, it is believed the interred was a middle-aged or older male of {{ill|Aristocracy|en|Aristocracy|qid=Q123432|lt=aristocratic|1=Aristocracy}} background.

The paintings have suffered the ravages of time, and, as {{ill|National Treasure (Japan)|en|National Treasure (Japan)|qid=Q1139795|lt=National Treasure|1=National Treasure (Japan)}} of Japan and [[:en:World Heritage|World Heritage]], their preservation has been accorded the highest priority. The entire tomb has been roofed over, and a series of adjoining antechambers were constructed to isolate the central chamber from temperature and humidity fluctuations, and prevent contamination by airborne [[:en:Mold (fungus)|mold]] spores and [[:en:microorganisms|microorganisms]].

